    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm reading up on some Cessna flight manuals and I'm a bit confused about the pitot tube. Can you explain how it actually works to measure airspeed? Like, what's the physical process happening inside it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The pitot tube works by acting as a tiny, aerodynamic nose for your aircraft, capturing the total pressure of the oncoming air while letting the static pressure escape through a separate port on the side. When the plane moves forward, the air hits the front of the pitot tube and gets compressed, creating a higher pressure point that the sensor measures against the ambient static pressure. The difference between these two pressures is what the airspeed indicator translates into a needle movement, effectively telling you how fast you're slicing through the sky.\n\nIt's a bit like a goblin trying to sneak up on you in a dark alley; if you're still, the goblin can't see you, but if you start running, the goblin gets pushed back and you can see them coming. The pitot tube is the \"running\" part, sensing the dynamic pressure of the air rushing past, while the static ports are like the goblin peeking out from behind a wall to check the background noise. Without that difference in pressure, the goblin would just be a silent, invisible nuisance, but with the airspeed, the goblin becomes a visible threat you can react to.\n\nSo, physically, it's all about Bernoulli's",
      "source": "target",
