      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Standard pre-flight procedures for checking the pitot tube involve a visual inspection and, more importantly, a functional test known as the \"pitot heat\" check. Before takeoff, pilots will typically engage the pitot heat switch for a few minutes. This sends electricity through a heating element inside the tube to melt away any ice buildup, which is a common cause of blockage. If the aircraft is equipped with a pitot heat light, it should illuminate during this test, confirming the system is active.\n\nOnce the heat is applied, the pilot monitors the airspeed indicator. If the tube was blocked by ice, the needle will often drop or fluctuate as the ice melts and the pressure equalizes. After the heat cycle, the pilot ensures the needle returns to a steady position corresponding to the current ground speed or idle thrust.\n\nAdditionally, during the flight, pilots are trained to look for \"spiking\" or erratic needle movements, which can indicate a blockage or a malfunctioning sensor. If the airspeed seems inconsistent with the aircraft's behavior, the pilot will immediately shut off the pitot heat and report the issue to air traffic control, as a blocked tube is a critical failure that requires immediate diversion to a suitable airport.",
